<page_title>Modeling Thermal Excitations and Radiationless Transitions</page_title>
<text> 
 

This article presents the classic method used in the Molecular Workbench to model two important processes in light-matter interactions: thermal excitations and radiationless transitions. The method is called classic because it is based purely on classic mechanics &#10102;.

Modeling thermal excitations

An atom cannot spontaneously excite its electrons without collisions with other atoms, because such a process will violate the Law of Momentum Conservation. If an electron is excited, the energy needed for the excitation must come from the kinetic energy of the atom, which will cause the momentum of the atom to decrease (because the kinetic energy is proportional to the square of momentum). The momentum of an electron relative to the atom is always zero, regardless of its state, because it is bound to it.

For an electron to be excited, the atom must collide with another. Let&apos;s assume that we have two atoms: atom A and atom B, which collide with each other. During the collision, an electron of atom A is excited from state i to state f. This process must satisfy both the Law of Momentum Conservation and the Law of Energy Conservation, which yields two equations: 

  

