Modeling radiationless transitions

An excited atom can fall to a lower energy state by emitting a photon or by transfering the energy to atoms. The latter is called the radiationless transition. Like the case of thermal excitation presented above, a radiationless transition cannot take place without involving another atom, because the conservation of momentum and energy cannot be both satisfied at the same time. Radiationless transitions are possible only when atoms collide. The constraints of momentum conservation and energy conser-vation give the same equations and solutions as above, but with the following difference:

   

This means that the solution always exists. There is no mathematical limitation for an electron to fall to a lower energy state and convert the excess energy into the kinetic energy of a colliding pair of atoms.

